Quoted By: >>48779022 >>48835280
I really liked this movie, it had a very good style of animation, each character looked and felt distinct and unorthodox. Like the fucking, spider carpenter or whatever he was, with the tophat and the goggles and the teeth, very different from what you'd expect but very good nonetheless. All the characters are very unsymmetrical in their design, even Rango is, considering his neck bends in the middle, which adds a lot of flavour and personality.
The story is a very classic heros journey and an homage to the Western. I mean, Clint Eastwood is literally the "Spirit of the West" in that film, and the movie has tons of cliches and stereotypes about the Western genre, but it respects them, which is very important. The themes explored in the story are the nature of the hero and his sacrifice, the life and death of the West and more fundamentally the life and death of the legend, the transformation one has when part of their journey of initiation, the crossing to the other side representing death and rebirth, and how you choose who you are in life.
It has surprisingly very good action scenes and a lot of spectacle, like the chase scene with the bats and the mole rats in the cannyon, and the final confrontation between Rango and Jake. Oh and that reminds me, Jake, what a fucking unit. He only appears for like 5 minutes but he fucking STEALS the show. He is intimidating and powerful, but he is not totally evil. Hell, his introduction put him, ironically enough, in the moral high ground against Rango, by exposing him for the fraud he is, driving him out of the town. At the end of the film however, Jake does begin to see Rango as his equal, as Rango formed his own legend, completing his personal journey and saving the town.
Overall 9/10
Anonymous
